title: For Sale/Trade:  ATTN: FELLOW 1911 FANS! CUSTOM STAINLESS KIMBER ULTRA CARRY 2
postcontent: When the time comes to get rid of/sell one of your favorite man toys, it’s like loosing your best friend. This is a 9mm stainless kimber ultra carry 2, in GREAT condition, that I personally customized. I installed Kimbers 2 hole design trigger (had the regular 3 hole) they only use on certain custom models, TruGlo TFX fiber optic & night sight combo, Wilson Combats extended slide stop, new complete recoil assembly from Kimber, and of course the hogue grip. I have the original box with owners manual and everything you would get buying new. It will come with 2 kimber mag (8RD), Fobus paddle holster (made just for Kimbers w/ Kimber written vertically on it). I’m not exaggerating when I say this shoots insanely accurate and has been 100% reliable; she’s a beauty and a beast. If you can’t figure out where I get my sale price at, then this probably isn’t the gun for you. I have no reason to lie when I say I’m loosing money on this, the slide stop alone was $60 (worth it to be able to reach it with your shooting hand). Why 9mm instead of .45? It’s a small lightweight conceal carry gun for one, you can carry at least 2 extra rounds, and it shoots very easy with all 9mm brands and grains. I have a couple friends with .45s in this and similar models, there’s a noticeable difference in recoil, it’s kinda funny when they want to shoot mine more then theirs. The sights are set for point of impact which I LOVE and at 7-10 yards she’s a tack driver. She can shoot much further but the range I go to is maxed out at 10 yards. 9mm ammo is cheaper, AND 9mm defense rounds have proven themselves in ballistic testing time and time again against 40sw and 45acp. ALWAYS cleaned and lubed her after every range trip, she deserves the attention when outshooting my buddies Dan Wesson and shot for shot with his Nighthawk. I get complimented every time I go to the range “what model is that, where’d you buy it? I’ve never seen a Kimber like that”. It makes me feel good about making something in a unique image. Why am I selling? Believe me I don’t want to, but the world is full of surprises (some good & some bad). I apologize for the long post but just wanted to make things clear and straight for my potential selling of this Kimber, I call her “Kimmy”. I can be reached at REDACTED. Here’s a link of what they cost newhttps://www.sportsmansoutdoorsuperstore.com/products2.cfm/ID/28413Contact with a text please and can send more pictures if desired. Reasonable offers considered, only trades would be a XDS, Glock 26, Glock 19, CZ P07, any quality 9mm PLUS cash of course.Would sell for less with 1 mag and without the holster but for what I’m asking for it, it’s a steal of a deal. title: For Sale/Trade:  EIG /Rohm model E1 (rg10) .22 short, the original Saturday Night Special!
location: West St. Louis County, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent: I'm an avid collector and came across this clean out my grandmother's attic at some point my grandpa must have bought one of these "Saturday night specials" as a protection it was wrapped up in a cloth in a box. These guns have some pretty cool historical reference as far as the 1968 weapons ban trying to eradicate cheap weapons such as these from entering the United States. This one was purchased by my grandfather in 50s based off the paperwork. For the age the gun is in great shape retaining over 90% of its original finish the only thing missing is the push rod which is missing on almost all of them. They were dubbed inferior guns and a lot of people say they're not even safe to shoot I have checked the tightness of the cylinder on this specific one and it is actually very tight and whines up so call me crazy but I have shot it several times for function testing but that is not a recommendation. These guns are mainly collected for their historical value, and not used ( although I know personally this one does function and doesn't spray let out the sides like the myths say!). I really have no sentimental value or use for the gun it will sit and be a good discussion piece or paperweight unless someone else can put it to use! 95 or best offer!

title: For Sale:  Rare Masters of Defense (MOD) Tempest Auto
postcontent: An original Masters of Defense (before they sold to Blackhawk) Janich Tempest Auto knife. This is the real deal and these are hard to find. There were originally 4 MOD auto knife models and the Tempest was one of them. MOD sold the company to Blackhawk in 2003 and quality went down from there. The original MOD blades were known for using superior materials and tight tolerances. They had a great reputation among the professional Mil and LE communities.This one is new old stock straight from my private collection. I've had it in the safe for well over a decade.No box. Never carried, sharpened, or used. Opens with authority. Locks up tight. Mint cond. These have a liner lock as opposed to pressing the button to release to fold.The pocket clip has a very small amount of play. I have not tightened it. Having slight play (movement) in the pocket clips was inherent to the early MOD blades - who knows why they didn't locktite them when they were built. Buyer is responsible for following any laws in their city/county.
